      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Contaminated Land and Underground Tanks: What Queensland Sellers Must Disclose
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Most Queensland sellers never need to think about land contamination. But for those selling former service station sites, dry cleaners, industrial lots, or properties with old underground tanks, the disclosure obligations are specific and the consequences of getting it wrong are serious.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The vast majority of residential properties in Brisbane's inner east will never have a contamination issue. But for sellers whose property has any history that might involve chemical storage, fuel, industrial use, or proximity to sites that do, the Queensland contaminated land disclosure regime is something to understand clearly before you list. The cost of ignoring it is significantly higher than the cost of dealing with it properly upfront.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What contaminated land means in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Under Queensland's Environmental Protection Act, contaminated land is land where soil or groundwater has been affected by chemicals, petroleum products, heavy metals, or other waste materials to a degree that creates a risk to human health or the environment. The contamination does not need to be severe or immediately hazardous to trigger disclosure obligations. The presence of contamination at levels that exceed relevant standards for residential land use is sufficient.</p>

      <p>Common contamination sources on residential properties include former underground fuel storage tanks (from earlier service station use or domestic heating oil storage), historical dry cleaning operations that used chemical solvents, agricultural or horticultural use involving pesticide or fertiliser storage, and industrial operations that stored or processed chemicals. The contamination does not always originate on the property itself: neighbouring sites can affect groundwater or soil through migration, which means properties adjacent to former industrial or commercial sites can carry contamination risk even if the property itself was always residential.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is most at risk</h2>
      <p>Sellers most likely to encounter a contamination issue fall into several categories. Former service station sites that have since been converted to residential use are the most common in Brisbane's inner east. Corner sites in post-war suburbs, particularly those that functioned as petrol stations or auto workshops through the 1960s and 1970s before rezoning, can retain underground infrastructure from that era. Old fuel tanks were not always decommissioned properly, and some remain buried under properties that current owners may not know about.</p>

      <p>Dry cleaners that operated before modern chemical handling standards changed industry practice used chlorinated solvents that are now classified as hazardous contaminants. Properties that housed these businesses, or that are adjacent to sites that did, can be affected. Similarly, former orchards or market gardens with decades of pesticide use can have residual chemical concentrations in the soil that exceed residential standards.</p>

      <p>For most sellers in Brisbane's inner suburbs, the risk is low. But low is not zero, and the only way to know your position with certainty is to check the register.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Queensland contaminated land register</h2>
      <p>The Queensland Government maintains a publicly accessible register of sites where contamination has been identified, is being investigated, or has been remediated. Buyers' solicitors check this register as part of standard contract due diligence, and the search results will be in front of the buyer's legal team before settlement. Sellers who discover their property is on the register at that point are not in a good negotiating position.</p>

      <p>Check the register before you list. If your property or an adjacent property appears, seek advice from an environmental consultant before you set a price or begin the sales process. Knowing your position at the outset allows you to manage the situation as a disclosed, priced element of the transaction rather than as a surprise that surfaces mid-contract and creates uncertainty for both parties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Underground storage tanks</h2>
      <p>Old underground storage tanks are more common in Brisbane's residential landscape than most sellers expect. In the 1950s and 1960s, domestic and commercial fuel storage was routine. Tanks installed for heating oil or equipment fuel were sometimes decommissioned informally or abandoned in place when the property changed use. Current owners may not know a tank exists under their property. The first indication is sometimes a buyer's building and pest inspection, a solicitor's search, or soil sampling during a renovation.</p>

      <p>If you are aware of an underground tank on your property, disclose it. If you suspect one may exist based on the property's history, consider engaging a specialist to investigate before listing. An undisclosed tank discovered post-sale by a buyer who can show you had reason to know about it is a significant legal and financial exposure. Addressing it before the campaign, even if the outcome is a confirmed decommissioned and cleaned tank with no ongoing risk, gives buyers accurate information and allows the property to be priced and marketed on a clear basis.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if you suspect contamination</h2>
      <p>Engage an environmental consultant before listing. A Phase 1 environmental site assessment reviews the history of the property and identifies whether there is a plausible contamination pathway. If the Phase 1 assessment identifies a risk, a Phase 2 assessment involves physical soil and groundwater sampling to determine the actual contamination level and what remediation, if any, is required.</p>

      <p>If contamination is confirmed, the decision to remediate before listing or to sell with the contamination disclosed and the price adjusted to reflect remediation cost is one to make with legal and agent advice. Properties with known contamination do sell in Queensland. They sell when the contamination is properly characterised, the remediation scope and cost is understood, and the price reflects that reality. They do not sell well when contamination surfaces mid-contract or post-settlement as an undisclosed issue.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if contamination is discovered after contract</h2>
      <p>A buyer who discovers contamination after the contract is signed and can demonstrate the seller was aware of it, or had reasonable grounds to be aware of it and failed to disclose, may have grounds to terminate the contract or seek a price reduction. The legal basis depends on the specific facts and the contract terms, but the exposure is real and the litigation process is expensive and disruptive even in cases where the seller ultimately prevails.</p>

      <p>The contrast with proper pre-contract disclosure is stark. A seller who discloses a known contamination issue in writing, before the contract is signed, and provides the environmental report to the buyer, has discharged their obligations. The buyer has made an informed decision. Even if the contamination affects the price the property achieves, the seller is in a legally clean position. That outcome is better than the alternative.</p>

